Maybe you’re brushing your teeth every day, but are you brushing correctly?

Taking the time to brush your teeth, two times a day for two minutes is more important than you think.

When brushing along the gumline, your toothbrush should be at a 45° angle.

Brushing harder is not better. You will brush away enamel and gum tissue.

Taking the time to do it right goes a long way. Try it tonight!😃

Dental Hygienist VS Dental Assistant

Thankfully, I work in an office where everyone gets along, but there is often a war between dental hygienist and dental assistants.

Dental assistants and dental hygienist both play a valuable role in a dental office and both have worked hard in different types of training, education and stressful certification exams.

Our goal should be to provide the best care possible for our patients and this can be accomplished when you work as a team.

Different types of dental cleanings

D1110 Adult prophy
healthy mouth- pocketing 1- 3mm no heavy build up

D1120 Child prophy primary or transitional dentition only

D4355 Debridement Heavy buildup on the teeth that interferes with ability of the dentist to perform a comprehensive oral evaluation

D4346 Scaling in the presence of moderate to severe inflammation
no radiographic boneless, moderate to severe gum inflammation, pocketing 4+mm

D4342 1-3 teeth per quad
Scaling and root planning
radiographic boneless present, pocketing 4-5mm or greater, inflammation and bleeding on probing, only completed on 3 or less teeth per arch

D4341 4+ teeth per quad
Scaling and root planing
radiographic boneless present, pocketing 4-5mm or greater, inflammation and bleeding on probing, completed on 4 or more teeth per arch

D4910 perio maintenance
patient had scaling and root planing completed and pocketing 4+ mm

One of the challenges I face as a dental hygienist is patients thinking they know it all.

There are times when I’m explaining to my patient their gum disease, and they are refusing to listen/believe.

In these cases, a few things I do are:

1. Listen to the patient and try to debunk some of their thoughts.

2. Use lots of visuals to educate my patient - I do this by handing them a mirror, using disclosing solution, using charts with educational information and reviewing X-rays.

3. Have someone else explain to them (usually the dentist)

4. Be patient and kind, but also know when to dismiss a patient especially if they are refusing treatment.

Calculus aka Tartar🦷

When plaque is not removed daily it hards on the tooth. At this point, you can’t brush or floss it away only a dentist or dental hygienist will be able to remove it.

How to prevent it?

1. Daily flossing
2. Brushing 2x a day for 2 mins
3. Drink your water
4. Choose healthy foods
5. Visit your dentist as recommended 
5. Don’t smoke

Different tips for different needs #WaterpikProPartner

The @WaterpikPro Aquarius Water Flosser includes different tips to help reach the most difficult areas and improve your patients' oral health.

The Classic Jet Tip — cleans between teeth and below the gumline.

The Orthodontic Tip — tapered brush removes hard-to-reach plaque around orthodontic brackets and wires. It also helps flush out bacteria and food debris from around the teeth and under the gums.

The Pik Pocket™ Tip — this tip is great for patients with periodontal pockets and furcations. It has a soft, latex-free rubber tip that is gentle and is clinically proven to access 90% of a 6mm pocket.

The Plaque Seeker™ Tip — a great tip to use around restorations. Has three thin tufts of bristles to access plaque around implants, crowns, bridges, veneers, and other areas that are especially susceptible to plaque accumulation.

The Water Flosser Toothbrush Tip — Designed to let you brush and water floss at the same time.

Healthy gums do not bleed 🦷🩸

Your gums could be bleeding for a number of reasons but it definitely isn’t normal to see blood as you’re brushing, flossing, or even as your dental hygienist is placing an instrument between your tooth and gum tissue aka periodontal probing.

Corporate VS private 

I work at a corporate-owned dental office, and I know corporate can get a bad rap, but honestly, I don’t agree. Every office has its pros and cons. You can work at a private office or a corporate office, and it can be absolutely horrible or amazing.

In my experience working at a corporate office, I have had the chance to work full time, receive benefits, and more access to tools I need to better treat my patients.

It’s difficult to say one is better than the other.  It really all comes down to how the office is ran.
